Educated Colloquial Hungarian \citep{siptar2000phonology} only maintains two of these paradigm distinctions, indicated in \colorbox{gray}{grey} in the table above. These are the {\sc 3sg.indef} indicative and the {\sc 1sg.indef} indicative. The (-ik) class has an (-ik) suffix instead of (-$\emptyset{}$) in the former and (-m) instead of (-k) in the latter. Otherwise, the regular and the (-ik) class are identical. Since (-m) is also the {\sc 1sg.def} ending, (-ik) stems neutralise the contrast in {\em definiteness} in this position.

This is shown in (1-2): \textipa{[tud]} `know{\sc.3sg.tr}' is a regular verb. It shows a contrast between the indefinite (1a) and the definite (1b). On the other hand, \textipa{[Esik]} `eat{\sc-3sg.intr}' is an (-ik) verb, which uses (-m) in both cases (2a-b).\\

\vspace{0.5cm}
\noindent 1 (a) \textipa{[tudok EJ pompa:S vits:Et]} `I know a fantastic joke.'\\
\hspace*{0.18cm} (b) \textipa{[tudom 6mit tudok]} `I know what I know.'\\
\vspace{0.5cm}


\noindent 2 (a) \textipa{[EsEm EJ kiS kE\textltailn{}ErEt]} `I eat a little bread.'\\
\hspace*{0.18cm} (b) \textipa{[EsEm 6 kE\textltailn{}ErEt]} `I eat the bread.'\\
\vspace{0.5cm}

\noindent However, the first person singular indefinite ({\sc 1sg.indef}) of the (-ik) verbs shows variance between the neutralising (-m) variant and the `regular' (-k) variant  (see (3)). I will refer to the (-m) variant as {\em marked} and to the (-k) variant as {\em unmarked}. This is because the (-m) variant {\em marks} the (-ik) stem in the {\sc 1sg.indef} and because it {\em neutralises} the contrast between the {\sc 1sg.indef} and the {\sc 1sg.def}.

\vspace{0.5cm}
\noindent 3 (a) \textipa{[it: l6kom pEStEn]} `I live here in Budapest.'\\
\hspace*{0.18cm} (b) \textipa{[it: l6kok pEStEn]} `I live here in Budapest.'\\
\vspace{0.5cm}

\noindent Apart from a set of hypercorrect, lexicalised forms (such as \textipa{[k\o{}\textltailn{}\o{}rg\o{}m]} `I implore you', cf.\ \textipa{[k\o{}\textltailn{}\o{}r\o{}g]} `implore{\sc .intr.3sg.indef}'), the variation between marked (-m) and unmarked (-k) is restricted to the {\sc 1sg.indef} of the (-ik) verbs only.

This variation is a socially salient linguistic marker \citep{kontra1997budapest}. The marked form is seen as the `correct'/prestige variant and shows both social stratification and style shifting.

When we compare Classic Literary Hungarian with Educated Colloquial Hungarian, we witness the retreat of the (-ik) conjugation paradigm, which is effectively restricted to {\sc 3sg.indef} and {\sc 1sg.indef} in the latter. This, coupled with the social salience of variance in the {\sc 1sg}, could indicate that the (-ik) paradigm is gradually disappearing (even if the (-ik) ending of the {\sc 3sg.indef} remains stable). 

This is reminiscent of the process of {\em morphological levelling}, in which verbs migrate from the minority category (the (-ik) class) to the majority category (the regular (-$\emptyset{}$) class) \citep{bybee1985morphology}. Levelling does not necessarily mean the eventual total disappearance of the minority class, as models exist of stable trade-offs between minority and majority categories in language \citep{cuskley2014internal}.

Most accounts of morphological levelling make one core assumption on the structure of the mental lexicon, the repository of words and constructions stored by the individual \citep{goldberg1995constructions}. This assumption is that the mental lexicon is rich in detail, similar to broader, non-domain-specific cognitive category systems \citep{racz2015morphological,goldinger1997words,nosofsky1988similarity}. As a consequence, words are organised according to similarity and that frequency or predictability of use affects the strength of the individual representations.

A rich-lexicon account of morphological levelling, then, rests on the principles of {\em frequency} and {\em prototypicality}. Here, both frequency and prototypicality are broader characteristics of cognitive category organisation that are applicable to the organisation of the human mental lexicon.

Frequency has two aspects. First, word types with higher {\em token frequency} are more prone to morphological suppletion and tend to resist replacement and morphological levelling \citep{pagel2007frequency,albright2003rules}. This can be easily seen in the case of the {\em copula}, which is one of the most frequent verbs and which shows rampant irregularity in almost every language. Second, word categories with higher {\em type frequency} tend to be more productive and to expand over time \citep{baayen1993frequency}. Within morphologically complex forms, the relative frequency of the constituent parts has a huge effect on how the form is processed \citep{hay2001lexical}. In a morphological levelling process, we expect more frequent types to resist levelling more.

Prototypicality has many working definitions, but it essentially relates to the {\em overall similarity} of a form to a given category \citep{gergely1994lexical,nosofsky1988similarity}. A form is said to be prototypical if it is very close to the centre of the category. We can quantify this distance in various ways. In terms of linguistic categories, prototypicality relates to the extent to which a given word form is {\em similar} to other forms in the same category. In a morphological levelling process, we expect word types that have higher token frequency and that are closer to the centre of the minority category to be more entrenched in the category and in the lexicon and, as a consequence, to resist levelling more.

In the light of all this, we have to answer the following questions. Is variance in the {\sc 1sg.indef} of the (-ik) class an instance of morphological levelling? If it is, how are the above principles manifest in this variation? Do we expect the (-ik) class to be completely levelled in with the regular class? How does social salience affect this process? In order to answer these questions, we first need to specify how the above, general, aspects of lexical organisation and morphological levelling apply to (-ik) verbs.

First, we ought to note that levelling should not be confined to variation in the {\sc 1sg.indef}. We would also expect verbs to lose the (-ik) ending in the {\sc 3sg.indef}. This is complicated by two facts. First, a large number of (-$\emptyset{}$)/(-ik) pairs are related but distinct in meaning (as in the above \textipa{[t\o{}r]}/\textipa{[t\o{}rik]} example). This semantic distinction can serve to maintain a formal distinction.

Second, a number of (-ik) verbs would be illicit unsuffixed free forms in Hungarian in the {\sc 3sg.indef} without the (-ik) suffix: \textipa{[\textltailn{}ugsik]}/\textipa{[*\textltailn{}ugs]} `calm-{\sc intr.3sg.indef}'. (Compare with \textipa{[ra:g-s]} `chew{\sc -2sg.indef}'.) I revisit these issues in Section \ref{discussion}.

Focussing on forms and the {\sc 1sg.indef}, we arrive at the following prediction:

\vspace{0.5cm}
\noindent (i) Verb forms that are attested with both (-ik) and {\em -$\emptyset$} forms will be more likely to use the {\em unmarked} {\sc 1sg.indef}.
\vspace{0.5cm}

\noindent If we take a form that has (-ik) in the {\sc 3sg.indef}, we expect it to prefer the {\em marked} {\sc 1sg.indef} overall: \textipa{[Esik]} $\rightarrow$ \textipa{[EsEm]} `eat' {\sc 3sg} / {\sc 1sg.indef}, \textipa{[l6kik]} $\rightarrow$ \textipa{[l6kom]} `stay' {\sc 3sg} / {\sc 1sg.indef}. Of course we expect to find unmarked forms as well, such as \textipa{[EsEk]}, \textipa{[l6kok]}. 

If the verb has no (-ik) in the {\sc 3sg.indef}, we expect the absence of a marked {\sc 1sg.indef}: \textipa{[Se:ta:l]} $\not\to$ \textipa{[*Se:ta:lom]} `walk' {\sc 3sg} / {\sc 1sg.indef}. If a verb is attested with both the (-ik) and the (-$\emptyset{}$) suffix, we expect it to be more likely to occur with the {\em unmarked} form in the {\sc 1sg.indef}. (\textipa{[bujdoS]}/\textipa{[bujdoSik]} `keep on hiding' $\rightarrow$ \textipa{[bujdoSok]}). This is because these verbs are lexically less prototypical members of the (-ik) class.

Pairs of closely related, but semantically distinct verbs would confound this analysis. However, there are no such pairs in the data (such as \textipa{[t\o{}r]} / \textipa{[t\o{}rik]}).

Membership in both the regular and the (-ik) class should also affect prototypicality for {\em suffixes}. As we will see, many of the (-ik) verbs end in productive derivational suffixes, such as {\em deadjectival} \textipa{(-odik)}/\textipa{(-Edik)}/\textipa{(-\o{}dik)} or {\em denominal} \textipa{(-zik)}. We expect that if a suffix is mostly attested with regular verbs versus {\em ik verbs}, this should manifest in a preference for the {\em unmarked} {\sc 1sg.indef} (-ik) suffix -- and {\em vice versa}:

\vspace{0.5cm}
\noindent (ii.a) Derived verbs in the (-ik) class will be more likely to use the marked {\sc 1sg.indef} if the suffix itself has an overall preference for (-ik) in the {\sc 3sg.indef}. \\
(ii.b) Derived verbs in the (-ik) class will be more likely to use the unmarked {\sc 1sg.indef} if the suffix itself has an overall preference for $\emptyset$ in the {\sc 3sg.indef}. 
\vspace{0.5cm}

\noindent In sum, the degree to which both the verb and its constituent parts are exclusive to the minority (-ik) class should have a strong effect on suffix preference in {\sc 1sg.indef}. The more the verb is closer to the centre of the (-ik) class, the more it should take the marked (-m) suffix that is characteristic of this class.

The general behaviour of the suffixes -- whether they occur with (-ik) or (-$\emptyset{}$) across forms -- will be probably relevant. It can be offset by properties of the verb stem, mainly its token frequency.

\vspace{0.5cm}
\noindent (iii) More frequent verbs in the (-ik) class will be more likely to use the marked {\sc 1sg.indef}.
\vspace{0.5cm}

\noindent This is because a frequent form should, in models of the richly detailed mental lexicon, enjoy more autonomy and should be more resistant to levelling pressure. Given the inverse correlation between word length and word frequency \citep{zipf1935psycho}, we expect longer forms -- that are less frequent -- to be less prone to use the marked form.

What other predictions can we draw from the interaction of frequency and prototypicality? Given that the marked {\sc 1sg.indef} neutralises {\em definiteness} marking in the {\sc 1sg}, we might expect (-ik) verbs that are {\em transitive} -- and therefore have attested definite forms -- to avoid using the marked indefinite in order to maintain expressivity:

\vspace{0.5cm}
\noindent (iv) If a verb in the (-ik) class has attested definite forms, it will avoid the marked indefinite form.
\vspace{0.5cm}

\noindent These numbered predictions follow if we regard variation in the {\sc 1sg.indef} of the (-ik) stems in Hungarian as a symptom of a morphological levelling process. They are straightforward to test on a representative sample of the ambient language \citep{hippisley2016cambridge}. I will use the Hungarian Webcorpus to explore the degree to which they define variation in the (-ik) class.

\section{The distribution of (-ik) variation}

Data were collected from the frequency dictionary of the Hungarian Webcorpus \citep{tron2006morphdb}. The dictionary is based on a version of the corpus that is morphologically analyzed \citep{tron2005hunmorph} and morphologically disambiguated on the inflection level \citep{halacsy2007hunpos}.

% mekkora a webkorpusz

The Webcorpus (specified as above) contains 3887 types and 2,549,651 tokens of (-ik) verbs. 3121 types have attested {\sc 1sg.indef} forms (164,627 tokens). I use an arbitrary cutoff rate to include verb types that have at least {\em four} {\sc 1sg.indef} forms in total. These verb types all show variation in the {\sc 1sg.indef}: they have at least one (-m) (marked) and one (-k) (unmarked) variant.

The size of this dataset is inflated by forms that are likely results of hypercorrect use. The author considers \textipa{[va:lom]} `transform{\sc -1sg.indef}' and \textipa{[Elva:lom]} `divorce{\sc -1sg.indef}' ungrammatical, but they are both attested in the webcorpus (with a token frequency of 3 and 1, respectively).

My analysis of the data largely follows Janda, Nesset \& Baayen's (\citeyear{janda2010capturing}) study of variation in Russian. I use the R open-source statistical environment for data analysis \citep{R} and the graphics package {\sc ggplot} for visualisation \citep{ggplot}. For each verb stem, I calculate the {\em odds ratio} of the marked and the unmarked {\sc 1sg.indef} form. In order to make it easier to visualise, analyse, and interpret the data, I take the logarithm of the odds. 

For instance, the verb \textipa{[bulizik]} `party{\sc -3sg}' has \Sexpr{d[d$lemma=='bulizik',]$freq_m+d[d$lemma=='bulizik',]$freq_um} attested {\sc 1sg.indef} forms in the data, out of which \Sexpr{d[d$lemma=='bulizik',]$freq_m} are marked and \Sexpr{d[d$lemma=='bulizik',]$freq_um} are unmarked (\textipa{[bulizom]}/\textipa{[bulizok]}). The odds ratio of marked/unmarked for this verb is \Sexpr{round(d[d$lemma=='bulizik',]$odds_m,2)}. The log odds is \Sexpr{round(d[d$lemma=='bulizik',]$log_odds_m,2)}.

