\section{Operationalising our predictors \label{operationalising}}

We now revisit the predictions of Section 1, repeated below.

\begin{enumerate}[i]
\item Verb forms that are attested with both (-ik) and $\emptyset$ forms will be more likely to use the {\em unmarked} {\sc 1sg.indef}.
\item
\begin{enumerate}
\item Derived verbs in the (-ik) class will be more likely to use the marked {\sc 1sg.indef} if the suffix itself has an overall preference for (-ik) in the {\sc 3sg.indef}. \\
\item Derived verbs in the (-ik) class will be more likely to use the unmarked {\sc 1sg.indef} if the suffix itself has an overall preference for $\emptyset$ in the {\sc 3sg.indef}. 
\end{enumerate}
\item More frequent verbs in the (-ik) class will be more likely to use the marked {\sc 1sg.indef}.
\item If a verb in the (-ik) class has attested definite forms, it will avoid the marked indefinite form.
\end{enumerate}

How can we test for these predictions? Given the fuzzyness of existing semantic criteria on argument structure, I opt for a form-based approach, categorising verbs according to overlap in the shape of the stem. 

For (i), I label the (-ik) verbs that are also attested without (-ik) in the {\sc 3sg.indef} in the Webcorpus: \Sexpr{nrow(d[d$verb_stem_varies==T,])} out of \Sexpr{nrow(d)} verbs in the dataset. One example is \textipa{[l6vi:rozik]} `manoeuvre{\sc -3sg.indef}', also attested as \textipa{[l6vi:roz]}. I operationalise the effect of these forms not by their frequency in the webcorpus, but rather by whether they are present or absent.

For (ii), I focus on the suffix class defined as {\em medial derivational suffixes} by \cite{eabaffy1978medial}, viz.\ \textipa{(-odik)}, \textipa{(-o:dik)}, \textipa{(-Edik)}, \textipa{(-\o{}dik)}, \textipa{(-\o{}:dik)}, as well as \textipa{(-doklik)}, \textipa{(-dEklik)}, \textipa{(-d\o{}klik)}, \textipa{(-l(ik))}, \textipa{(-ll(ik))}. My inspection of the \Sexpr{nrow(d)} variable (-ik) stems reveals a third frequent derivational suffix, the {\em denominal} (-zik).

I group these variants into three classes, fully productive (-Odik) (\textipa{[o/o:/\o{}/\o{}:dik]}) more lexicalised (-lik), as well as (-zik). I mark membership in these three classes for all verbs in my dataset. The single criterion of membership is formal similarity -- the {\sc 3sg.indef} of the verb has to end in (-Odik), (-lik), or (-zik).

For each suffix (the term {\em ending} might be more accurate, given the primacy of formal similarity in defining these classes), I count the number of {\em types} in the Hungarian Webcorpus, {\em with or without -ik}: \textipa{(-od)}, \textipa{(-o:d)}, \textipa{(-\o{}d)}, \textipa{(-\o{}:d)} versus \textipa{(-odik)}, \textipa{(-o:dik)}, \textipa{(-\o{}dik)}, \textipa{(-\o{}:dik)}, \textipa{(-\o{}:dik)}; (-l versus (-lik), and (-z) versus (-zik). 

I do not consider all possible variants.

First, {\em deadjectival} (-Odik) has a fifth variant, front unrounded \textipa{(-Edik)}. This latter one, {\em without -ik}, overlaps with a separate verbal ending, (-Ad). As we will see, this is a relatively frequent form, so that \textipa{(-Edik)} is an exception to the overall pattern of (-Odik). We ought to also note that (-Odik) and (-zik) are fully productive, while (-lik) is not. This is excluded.

Second, I also exclude counts of (-ll) and (-llik). The former is a very rare verb ending, and so should not be compared to the latter. In order to control for this, only counts of (-l) and (-lik) are included. The summary can be seen in Table \ref{suffixtable} below.


