Subsuming \textipa{(-odik)}, \textipa{(-o:dik)}, \textipa{(-\o{}dik)}, \textipa{(-\o{}:dik)} under the shorthand (-Odik) is idiosyncratic to this paper, as capital letter notations in morphophonology usually refer to allomorphs of the same morpheme. Short- and long-vowel variants of (-Odik) can also be analysed as separate suffixes (see \citealt{kiefer2000strukturalis}).

Given that pairs of stems with (-ik) and (-$\emptyset{}$) (like \textipa{[t\o{}r]}/\textipa{[t\o{}rik]}) exist, a speaker can re-analyse -ed(ik), -Od(ik), -l(ik), and -z(ik) as pairs. 

That is, one might assume that  \textipa{[jElEz} `signify{\sc -3sg.indef}' and \textipa{[ut6zik]} `travel{\sc -3sg.indef}' share a verbal derivational suffix, except that the latter is also an (-ik) stem. Then, a speaker has strong evidence that (-Od)/(-Odik) is a more typical (-ik) suffix, whereas [-l]/[-lik] is a more typical (-$\emptyset{}$) suffix. The presumed suffix (-z)/(-zik) has strong support for existing both as an (-ik) and a (-$\emptyset{}$) suffix.

