Second, verbs that show variation between (-d) and (-s) in their conjugation show marked preferences. The (-d)/(-s) stems are a specific subclass of (-ik) verbs. It is possible for (-d)/(-s) forms to co-exist in one paradigm slot, as in \textipa{[vErEkEdik]}/\textipa{[vErEksik]} `fight{\sc -3sg.indef}' or \textipa{[mElEgEdik]}/\textipa{[mElEgsik]} `get warm{\sc -3sg.indef}'. For other verbs, the (-d)/(-s) forms co-exist within the paradigm, but have a set distribution, as in \textipa{[fEkydnE]} `lie{\sc -3sg.cond.indef}' / \textipa{[fEksik]} `lie{\sc -3sg.indef}'. This is because the conditional suffix (-AnA) goes with the (-d) variant.

Here, the relevant aspect of this variation is that (-sik) forms overwhelmingly prefer the {\em marked} suffix in the {\sc 1sg.indef}, while (-dik) forms prefer the {\em unmarked} suffix. This despite the fact that (-Odik), overall, shows a preference for the marked suffix. This can be seen in Table \ref{szikdiktabla}, which reports the mean odds of the marked and the unmarked form for (i) all forms, (ii) forms ending in (-dik), (iii) forms ending in (-sik).

